8 Support Poll Results That Prove Donald Trump Is Serious
Some have tried to label him as a wind vane.
Some people think he's just a joke.
Some are waiting for a collapse.
Although some Republicans have tried to get Donald Trump off the top of the polls, it has not (yet) been successful.
Of the last 11 national polls in ten, Donald Trump has been in the lead by a double-digit figure, and some have begun to seriously consider what this means for the nomination of a real estate king.
Of course, the election is only at an early stage.
These results do not yet mean that Trump is likely to become a Republican candidate.
Commentators point out that at this point in 2011, Rick Perry was losing his lead to rising Herman Cain, neither of whom got behind any states in the nomination process.
There are also many reasons why he would have problems in the general election.
However, outside groups such as Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative economic organization Club for Growth have noted Trump's persistence and have begun to use their funds to bring him down.
The following recent support survey results suggest that the real estate king is not just a passing stage:
Trump’s popularity figures have turned around.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, Monmouth University endorsement polls showed that only two Republicans out of ten welcomed the property king.
By mid-July, the figure was 40 per cent.
At the beginning of August, the figure was 52 per cent.
Currently, six out of ten Republicans welcome Donald Trump.
About three out of ten say they are negative.
These figures are also true in the first primary states.
In a poll conducted by Quinnipiac University in Iowa last week, 60 percent of Republicans said they welcomed Trump.
Two-thirds of Republican voters would be happy if Trump became a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "excited" or "satisfied" if Trump was the candidate.
Only two out of ten said they would be "shocked" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson has the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent "excited" vs. Trump's 40 percent).
The next most exciting?
Marco Rubio at 21%.
On the other hand, 47% of Republican voters would be "unsatisfied" or "shocked" if Jeb Bush, the favorite in power, became a candidate.
Trump’s fiery nature is not a problem for most Republicans.
Although Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his pompous speeches and insults, according to Monday's ABC News/Washington Post poll, 52% of Republican-leaning voters at the national level think that the property king has the right character for the president.
According to Quinnipiac's survey last week, the number in Iowa, the state that organizes the first convention, is the same: 52 percent of Republicans think Trump has the right character for the leader.
However, according to a survey by ABC/Post, 44 percent think that his character is inappropriate to be president, and nearly six in ten think that his character does not belong in the White House.
Republicans are getting used to the idea.
When Republican voters think like commentators, they think Trump is a real option.
According to a CNN/ORC survey, four out of ten considered Trump the most likely option when asked who is most likely to be nominated as a Republican candidate.
At the end of July, four out of ten supported Jeb Bush.
Republican voters have not always had access to the brightest crystal ball possible.
At this time in the last legislature, four out of ten Republicans felt that Rick Perry would be nominated, and only 28% supported the final candidate, Mitt Romney.
In any case, this shows that the majority of Republican voters find the Trump campaign credible.
Even if the Republicans stood for a second candidate, Trump would still win almost everyone.
Some commentators have pointed out that the fragmented field is likely to have contributed to Trump's leadership, as anti-Trump support is divided among numerous other candidates.
However, a poll conducted by Monmouth University in early September showed that in a hypothetical bilateral race between Trump and almost all other Republican candidates, Trump will gain majority support in almost all cases.
He leads Carly Fiorina with 13 points, Marco Rubio with 14 points, Walker with 15 points, Jeb Bush with 19 points, and Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie each with 33 points.
He's tied with Ted Cruz.
The only Trump winning candidate?
If they were pitted against each other, Ben Carson would beat businessman Trump by a big 18 point difference.
The majority of Donald Trump supporters have said they have made the decision.
A new CBS/NYT poll on Tuesday shows that only slightly more than half of the pro-Trump voters have decided who to vote for.
Of course, the situation can change, and no one can say for sure that he will never change his mind.
46% said they could change candidates.
In any case, Trump’s biggest rival at the moment is another unlikely winner, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but those voters who said they made the decision are twice as likely to be on Trump’s side.
Six out of ten Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Since Donald Trump two months ago called Mexican immigrants "rapists" in his campaign opening speech, immigration has been at the center of the 2016 debate.
Some are concerned that Trump's pomp will drive Hispanic voters further away from the Republican Party and hurt rebranding attempts.
According to a new ABC/Post poll released on Monday, six out of ten Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So it seems that as long as immigration is at the center of things, so is Donald Trump.
Frustration with the government has reached a new peak.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson's support now covers about half of Republican voters, largely due to their position outside politics.
Six out of ten Republicans said Monday in an ABC/Post poll that they would rather choose someone outside of politics than someone with government experience.
They're angry at the federal government, too.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll from Iowa two weeks ago showed that three out of four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with Republicans in Congress: 54 percent are "unsatisfied" and 21 percent are "really angry".
First appearance of Jeremy Corbyn in Prime Minister's Question Time
Corbyn's first appearance in Question Time has been eagerly awaited since his election.
Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn meets David Cameron for the first time in Prime Minister's Question Time.
Corbyn rises to ask his first of six questions shortly after noon, and probably both the media and Labour MPs will be watching his performance closely.
Corbyn has called for "less theater and more facts" for this weekly screening.
He has also said that he could leave some of the opportunities to his colleagues.
This encounter is the first parliamentary test of Corbyn's leadership since he was appointed to the Shadow Government and spoke at the annual meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand quietly during the national anthem at Tuesday's memorial service held on the 75th anniversary of the Battle for Britain air war has sparked criticism among Conservative Party MPs and appeared in a number of front page articles.
Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesperson for Corbyn said he "standing reverently quietly" and that he recognizes "the bravery of the Royal Air Force in the British Air War."
A member of Corbyn's shadow government, Owen Smith, stated to the BBC Two Newsnight programme that he would have urged the Labour leader to sing the national anthem despite the fact that he felt the royal house should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to be part of Corbyn's inner circle, citing disagreements on economic, defence and foreign affairs.
BBC policy correspondent Robin Brant says that the policy differences regarding the party's status in the European Union as well as the government's aid ceiling have also "clumped" within the Labour Party since Corbyn's appointment.
Corbyn said at a trade union confederation meeting that the Labour Party is proposing a change that would remove the entire roof.
Hours later, the shadow government's Labor and Pensions Secretary Smith stated that the party was "quite clear" that they were only opposed to the government's plans to lower the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,000.
Corbyn becomes the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the past decade, when he has been leader of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader has promised a new approach to politics and now says that he has "crowded" ideas into questions for the Prime Minister, and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
Islington North MP Corbyn has said that the Prime Minister's Question Time is too confrontational and that he intends to refrain from both witty wording and prickly talk, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and youth challenges.
Corbyn has said that the shadow government's finance secretary, Angela Eagle, will replace her in question classes when Corbyn is not attending - for example, when Cameron is abroad.
Mr Corbyn has also suggested that other colleagues could sometimes be allowed to speak, and he has said that he approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, on the subject.
When Cameron took the lead in 2005, he said he wanted to move further away from the kind of political theater that is often associated with the Prime Minister's questioning hours, but he later had to admit he failed.
Since they began to be televised in 1990, Question Time by the Prime Minister has been an important measure in assessing the leader's discretion, his control of the House of Commons, and his position among other MPs, although critics have criticized Question Hours for becoming nothing more than a travesty that requires far-reaching reforms.
