Metcash launches grassroots campaign against intrusion into Aldi sector
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from Aldi's invasion of southern and western Australia.
Metcash, a food wholesaler, has launched a grassroots campaign to defend the market share of IGA traders in South and Western Australia before Aldi's $700 million attack.
Aldi is preparing for the opening of two distribution centers as well as the first store early next year in South and Western Australia, where up to 120 stores are coming. At the same time, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food intermediaries and building an IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing as well as events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA merchants and suppliers have jumped in, and brands such as Simmo's, an ice cream maker from Dunsborough, offer tastings in IGA stores, and store owners sell discounted tickets to Australian football matches to their loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defense strategy on September 29, as this food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler organizes an annual investor strategy day.
There’s a lot at stake, with South and Western Australia making up nearly 30% of Metcash’s IGA trading area, with higher profit margins than the IGA network in the eastern states of Metcash.
Visitors to shopping in South and Western Australia are notoriously parochial, with IGA dealers having a much higher market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: over 30% in the South and 24% in the West, compared to 14% in the Eastern States.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will capture about 5% of the food market in the two states within 12 months of the opening of the first stores.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA dealers could lose $360 million annually in sales and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 stores in the west next year, generating sales of $500 and $600 million in these areas.
Loss of food and food sales and amounts at Metcash's high fixed cost base can cost Metcash about $13 million in operating profit losses before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
Meanwhile, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states mainly to Ald and Coles, although a recent Roy Morgan study found that IGA customers were the most loyal of all.
Morgan Stanley believes that Metcash's food and food sales will decline by 3.8% in 2016, 4.1% in 2017 and 2.1% in 2018, so that its market share will drop from 14% in 2015 to 10.3% in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, manager of the leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could "very possibly lose in a decade".
Metcash has refused to respond publicly to Douglass' comments.
However, it has been understood that a Metcash board member would have contacted Douglass last week.
Since 2010, IGA’s market share has fallen from 18% to 14%, and the revenue from Metcash’s food and food business, which supplies products to some 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43% since 2012, reflecting a reduction in the debt financing of operations under pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler stands up, and has invested more than $150 million annually in reducing the prices of hundreds of products weekly to the same level as Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA dealers renovate stores by adding faster growing fresh food, and bringing a better range of private brand products to the market.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says that lower prices and improved stores have increased the appeal, and he hopes that the wholesaler will return to the path of revenue growth in 2017, for the first time in four years.
Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy supports Thanasi Kokkinakis
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves honor rather than criticism for his behavior
Thanasi Kokkinakis has suffered as a bystander in a recent storm that has raged around his friend Nick Kyrgios. He deserves credit rather than criticism for his own behavior, says Steve Healy, president of the Australian Tennis Association.
A junior member of the talented duo called "Special Ks" Kokkinakis was unwittingly exposed to a case in which Kyrgios annoyed Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters competition.
Shortly after, in a fiery qualifier match in Cincinnati, the chief judge was twice forced to separate Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison when Harrison declared, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beat that brat."
Although Kokkinakis was last seen breaking his bat after a cramp ruined his potential victory over Richard Gasquet at the US Open, Healy has been a staunch defender of Kokkinakis.
Right now, the young man is in Glasgow competing with Sam Groth for another place in doubles with Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Britain.
"I'm pretty strongly of the opinion that Thanasi is just being pulled into his brawl," Healy said.
He broke his bat when he lost due to a cramp in the US Open, but he's not the first player to break his bat in frustration, and I know Thanas well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But he’s behaved very well, even in quite provocative situations at the US Open with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves praise.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he has been treated a little harshly.
He is very mature for a 19-year-old, he works hard, fits into the team and so on, and has never had problems with other players. He is appreciated in the dressing room, he trains hard, is in good shape and is quite a calm and mature young man, and I think he should be judged according to his merits.
Healy has also supported the decision not to include Kyrgios in the important games starting on Friday, describing this "joint decision" as a good solution for all, but still supporting the Canberraman's return to the team's regular equipment.
"We want the team to be completely focused on the games and not all the controversy around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And Nick has grown up really fast, as Federer and Murray have pointed out, and he is growing up in public, and he has made some terrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he has received. However, we are trying to support him, we are trying to help him understand the consequences of his actions, and I think it is best for both the team and him if he spends some time away from the public to reflect on these consequences.
European migration crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes borders, arrests migrants
Hungary declared a state of emergency and closed its southern border with Serbia, arresting those who tried to enter illegally, with the aim of damming the flow of migrants entering the country.
Chaos ensued at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in neutral territory, and Serbian authorities reacted with dismay.
