PHE released this " landmark" report last month, describing it as a "comprehensive review of evidence".
However, several researchers have questioned the sustainability of the data and referred to links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
Last month, the medical journal Lancet published an editorial attacking the "extraordinaryly sluggish bottom" of PHE's main conclusion.
Two other researchers who wrote in the BMJ have wondered if the claims were "built on rock or sand."
Martin McKee, Professor of Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, say, "The main principle of public health is that policies must be based on proven effectiveness."
They say that the public expects that PHE's claim "to date, according to the best estimate, e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than conventional cigarettes" is based on a detailed assessment and modeling of the evidence.
In fact, it comes from a single meeting of 12 people who developed a multi-criteria decision analysis model (MCDA) to synthesize their opinions on harm associated with various nicotine-containing products, and the results of this meeting were summarized in the study.
McKee and Capewell say one of the sponsors of the meeting was the company named EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive is reported to have previously received funding for research independent of Bristish American Tobacco.
He also supported BAT's public health mandate in the sustainability report, they say.
One of the 12 people at the meeting reported receiving funding from an e-cigarette manufacturer, but not the funding he reportedly received earlier from the tobacco company Philip Morris International, they added.
The criteria for the selection of panel members are not stated, but the panel includes several well-known e-cigarette supporters, some of whom also report that the study has received funding from the sector.
Others present are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The meeting was also attended by the Director of Tobacco at PHE.
The study produced by the group "muchly admits" that there is a lack of "undisputed evidence regarding harm in most of the products and in most of the criteria," McKee and Capewell write.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell say PHE's claims that "so far there is no evidence that e-cigarettes serve as a route to smoking in children or non-smokers" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of health and well-being at PHE, said the claims made in the BMJ had been answered in the past.
He says, "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking."
Half of those who burn their lives die of addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks posed by e-cigarettes are relatively small, but we must continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear obligation to inform the public about what the evidence shows and what it does not show, especially when there is so much public uncertainty about relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Nearly 80,000 people die each year from a smoking-related illness and smoking costs the NHS £2 billion each year.
By explaining the current evidence - that is, while e-cigarettes are not risk-free, their disadvantages are only a fraction of the harm of traditional tobacco - we are fulfilling our national responsibilities.
