"Sound genetics" allows brain cell control through sound waves
The video shows how shuttle worms change direction as soon as the sound impulse hits them.
Scientists have grown worms with genetically engineered neural systems so that they can be controlled by sound wave bursts.
Tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses work by switching on genetically modified motion nerve cells with membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Scientists are reading and writing brain activity with light
The researchers said that worms demonstrate the functionality of a new method called sound genetics, in which ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep-brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are introduced into people's brains to treat Parkinson's disease.
The shuttles normally do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when surrounded by a liquid with microscopically small bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified the ultrasound waves, which then pass inside the worms.
Reinforced ultrasound waves affect TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open up and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in Nature Communications.
To produce ultrasonically controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motion nerve cells have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound on modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they turn on the modified motion nerve cells.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn nerve cells on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent along the optical fiber to the desired point within the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that using gene therapy and the therapeutic virus may make it possible to make the target human nerve cells respond momentarily to the ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
