8 Golden Rules for Living in a Student Dorm
It's been 11 years since I moved into a student dorm at the age of 19, when I believed in berets and moral relativism, but it's only now that I remember the forced smiles of the people I annoyed and the numerous, long complaints about others.
Much of what I learned can be summed up in eight simple rules.
Moving into a dorm can be anything from nerve to completely scary.
It’s tempting to babble: tell me where you’re from, if you had a year off and where, what you think of Corbyn, and why “I don’t really love or hate Marmite because it’s really just a yeast extract HAHAHA finds me in my room.”
Take a breath.
And also help others to take a breath - ask questions and show interest.
It guides the conversation and helps you find the people you like, rather than the ones you don’t want to talk to even if your eyelashes are on fire and they’re handing out fire extinguishers.
Give people space.
People’s rooms often turn into cocktail parties, movie nights, and general entertainment places, but they are also the places where people dress and repair their underwear.
Don’t even think about starting college when you’re in a relationship.
College is a tough place for introverts.
Your room should be a place of rest, but many dormitories form a culture of wandering from room to room, which is friendly, social and causes lifelong friendships.
It could mean hell for someone trying to rest.
Nothing in this culture gives you permission to say, “I like you and I want to be friends with you, but you have to leave now so I can collect back the energy I spent talking to you.”
Try to sense when a student friend is tired of socializing - and maybe send a text message to the door instead of knocking.
Knocking when there was a speech: knock.
One guy in my dorm thought that if the door wasn't locked, he was invited in.
He saw quite a few things.
Make friends through baking.
Since you start college in the peak season of the baking trend, knocking on people's doors with a chocolate cake plate and self-presentation seems somewhat less strange, less "welcome to the neighborhood, I baked you something, now smile when I ask you personal questions" -50s.
Offering self-made treats is a great way to make friends.
Your roommates feel obligated to talk, and it may be that in the future they will associate your face with a tasty surprise.
Of course, this depends on whether you can bake.
Poorly mixed flour-sugar-fat lumps are likely to cause people to just pretend to sleep when you knock.
Stealing food is a common crime in student dorms.
Understandably, taking a chicken is stealing, but what if you just take a drop of milk in your tea?
Ask and check with the owner of the milk.
It is quite possible that they will give you permission, even if they are boiling internally.
