The U.S. Federal Reserve is sitting two days around a huge mahogany table this week at a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise the policy rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At the other end of the central bank's decorative, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that the president of the Federal Reserve, Janet L. Yellen, and her colleagues, must put the nation's financial interests above everything else.
Congress has placed on the central bank a dual responsibility: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
After the Great Depression, however, central bank leaders have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is this third requirement that could be a decisive factor in a decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted, whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record-breaking incentive that has been brought by short-term interest rates that have remained almost zero since late 2008.
While most of the data shows a steady growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made already on alert central bank officials even more alarmed when it comes to increasing instability, fearing what would be the impact of raising the federal funds rate by even a percentage point per quarter.
“Understandingly, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important issues to be monitored,” says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial expert at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"I believe, however, that if they are looking for justification to leave interest rates unchanged, the increased uncertainty in world markets is valid enough to wait yet," he says.
No agreement has been reached on the central bank’s decision, which is also a source of nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg study, about half of financial experts predict interest rates will rise this week.
On the other hand, the financial markets expect the central bank to delay the drawdown, as the key indicator indicates that the chance of growth is only around 30%.
This suggests a decline in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, unless policymakers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next drawdown will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, with a new figure of 16,599.85.
The recovery was accompanied by the expectation that the central bank will keep the level unchanged this week, says John Lonski, chief financial expert at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It's surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now," he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, "they will have to put a lot of effort into their policies to support the financial markets so that they do not panic."
Other experts argue that an increased level would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty as to when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it appeared that the central bank would be raising interest rates this month by a quarter of a percentage point, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite liberals calling for more economic development in their complaints.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1%, the lowest rate in seven years and close to the level the central bank sees as the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of picking up.
Although inflation is still below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, the main reason for this, according to the central bank’s decision-makers, is the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "is able to cope with higher interest rates and also needs them in view of the tight conditions in the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief financial expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 16 percent from its May record as investors feared China’s slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10% below the peak in May.
For central bank decision-makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in a complex equation that tells when interest rates should be raised.
"Without these financial market events and recent weeks of news coverage of China's economic weakness, decision-makers would raise levels at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior investigator at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve official.
He now predicts that policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the effects.
“The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still rather unclear and they have little information at their disposal as to the consequences of the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the monetary authority of the world.
In recent years, the central bank’s influence has been enormous.
In 2013, Ben S. Bernanke, then president, hinted that the central bank could "narrow" the increase in the amount of money, caused upheavals in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank's decision-making process is "more art than science," says Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management company Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "the central bank has in the past overreacted to financial market movements that have appeared to be separate from the fundamentals of the economy."
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in interest rates, and Lacker, a voting member of the committee, cites the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its reference value by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings "despite its limited, identifiable effects on U.S. economic growth," Lacker says.
A year later, these cuts were reversed by the central bank.
The central bank should only prioritize financial stability during a major crisis, such as when markets collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Pose, former member of the Bank of England's interest-setting committee.
The latest turmoil does not come close to its level, Posen says.
“Nobody wants to be in a situation where there is fear of raising interest rates because the market is annoyed,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability, as long as that is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
