Weight Loss Surgery May Help Mildly Obese Diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after weight loss surgery than those treated in ways other than surgery.
“It takes a long time to get the mortality data,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery specialist who wrote an editorial for the new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In weight loss or bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but the majority of subjects in the study have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI, the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If a BMI is over 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if a person has a BMI over 30, they are considered obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery and gastric reduction, with medicinal treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of people cut down from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of those who were treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same in 29.
Thirty-six percent of the patients were fully and 28 percent partially cured with diabetes.
In comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes improved completely by only 1% and in part by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and the "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgery group," the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood haemoglobin levels of A1c, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers write.
Post-operative haemoglobin levels of A1c dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at approximately 8%.
However, this improved “glycemic control” described by improved haemoglobin levels of A1c did not reduce mortality over five years, said Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The team also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
By the fifth year, when compared to the group undergoing gastric reduction surgery, the group undergoing gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (18,7 and 14.2 kg), decreased their BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), decreased their haemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 and 2.1%), and were more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 and 16.7%).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoelix says that although the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden, where the surgery led to longer lifespans in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who underwent weight loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die in a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study does not show an improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says the results are nonetheless encouraging for individuals with a BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
“The results of the study are crucial precisely in showing that surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group,” he says, and does not involve an increased risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their physicians should take weight very seriously when the patient’s BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we'll wait too long before we take this seriously," he says.
I believe that once a person has collected these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
