Glencore Raises $2.5 Billion in Share Sale
Swiss-based mining giant Glencore, who suffered a commodity price crash, raised $2.5 billion on Wednesday by selling shares as part of its extensive debt-cutting plan.
Glencore, listed on the London Stock Exchange, said in a statement that it had sold some £1.6 billion in new shares to reduce its debt.
The company, which lost 57% of its market capitalization this year, is struggling with the price of collapsed commodities as the slowdown in the Chinese economy puts a strain on demand and wreak havoc on all markets.
The new subscription put the value of Glencore shares at the top of the London Stock Exchange in Wednesday morning trades.
Shares rose 2.77 percent to 131.60 pence in the FTSE 100 index, which opened 0.69% higher.
Glencore had revealed a $2.5 billion stock deal the previous week as part of its broader plan to cut its $30 billion debt burden by about a third.
The company sold the new share capital for 125 pence a share, which meant a 2.4 percent reduction in Tuesday's closing price.
The company sold 1.3 billion shares at a total value of 9.99 percent of the group.
Concerns about China’s long-standing stagnation have cut iron ore prices by about half, while prices of coal, copper and other commodities have fallen by 20-40 percent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a statement released Tuesday by the White House confirmed.
Xi's first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and is a response to President Barack Obama's visit to Beijing last November.
U.S. President and First Lady Michelle Obama will host a dinner for Xi and his wife Peng Liyuan after the leaders hold bilateral talks.
"Prince Xi's visit will provide an opportunity to expand cooperation between the United States and China on numerous global, regional and bilateral issues of common interest, while at the same time allowing President Obama and President Xi to constructively discuss issues of disagreement," the statement added.
On a visit that was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to stop by Seattle on his way to Washington to meet with numerous U.S. technology leaders, before continuing towards New York City and the United Nations General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss numerous controversial topics, including Washington's concern over China's alleged cyber espionage and the country's increased absoluteness in the disputed waters of the South China Sea.
