Xi urges to open up the economy to the wider world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group on Tuesday that is tasked with guiding reform.
"China should commit itself to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the Group leading the deepening of the overall reform.
Supporting openness, while driving forward reforms, increases new momentum and vitality, and creates new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The management team adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list limiting market access, a relaxation of border control principles, a call on state-owned companies to seize private capital, and a revision of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created to identify the sectors and companies in which no investment is allowed.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant as it gives the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more open.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open up government-controlled sectors to private financiers, more sectors will be opened up.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent resident permits for foreigners, "green cards", is facilitated by optimizing the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed guaranteeing the professional rights of lawyers and supporting professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, said in a statement released after the meeting.
